A perfectly ripe red or green bell pepper. Can be used to talk about bell peppers or food in general.
A long, green cucumber with bumpy skin. Resembles its derived product, a pickle or gherkin, on many platforms, except on Apple and WhatsApp, which depict it with light-green, seed-y slices.

A head of a rich green leaf vegetable, usually shown with white stalks. May be used to represent a variety of greens, including romaine lettuce, chard, and Chinese cabbage like bok choy, as commonly cooked in Asian cuisines.
A rich green, tree-like head or floret of broccoli.
A single white or light brown bulb of garlic. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or vampire protection.
A round yellow onion. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or crying. Sometimes used in metaphors about layers. Might also be used in computing contexts in reference to onion routing.
The edible fungus of the mushroom, depicted as a toadstool with a white-spotted red cap and stem.
The pod of the peanut, shown in its rounded, grooved, light-brown shell. Apple depicts a pair.
The reddish-brown, acorn-shaped chestnut, tapering to a sharp tip from its light brown base on most platforms. A popular roasted snack associated with autumn and Christmas.
A loaf of white or wheat bread, as before it is sliced for toast or sandwiches.
The flaky, golden-brown crescent of a croissant, a breakfast pastry associated with France and Austria.
The long, thin loaf of a baguette, with scoring on its golden-brown crust. A bread commonly associated with France.
A round piece of flatbread with grill marks. Used to represent any type of flatbread, soft or crunchy.
The heart-shaped twist of a hard or soft golden-brown pretzel, seasoned with grains of salt. A snack commonly associated with Germany.

The brown bread of a bagel, shown sliced in two halves. Some platforms depict seeds, as sesame or poppy, and a schmear of cream cheese, with the bagel assembled as a sandwich. May resemble the Doughnut at small sizes.
A stack of breakfast pancakes, topped with a pad of butter and maple syrup oozing down its golden-brown sides, onto a plate on some platforms.
A round or square Belgian waffle, baked to a golden brown. Most platforms depict this emoji topped with a pad of butter, and some include gooey syrup running down the sides.
A wedge of yellow-orange cheese with holes, like a Swiss, but used for the food in general. May be used for various cheese-related slang expressions (e.g., “cheesy,” “say cheese,” “big cheese”).
A hunk of unspecified meat on a white bone, as associated with cartoon cavepersons or food in anime and manga (Japanese ano niku, “that meat”).
A crispy brown leg (drumstick) of chicken, duck, turkey, or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants.
A cut of uncooked red meat, as a T-bone or rib-eye steak, with the light, white marbling of fat.
Strips of crispy, fatty, reddish-brown bacon, as fried for breakfast. Depicted as a pair on most platforms.
A burger with a beef patty, usually depicted on a sesame bun with cheese, lettuce, and tomato—making it a cheeseburger, though officially called Hamburger by Unicode.
Thin-cut, golden-brown French fries, served in a red carton, as at McDonald’s. Apple features Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes on its carton.
A slice of pepperoni pizza, topped with black olives on Google. WhatsApp adds green pepper, Samsung white onion.
The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game.
A sandwich, as eaten at lunch, made with lettuce, tomato, and cheese on slices of white or wheat bread. Apple, Google, and WhatsApp add a deli meat that resembles ham.

A Mexican or Tex-Mex taco on a hard or soft corn tortilla, filled with such ingredients as beef, lettuce, tomato, cheese, and onion. Apple’s design resembles a carne asada taco, with cilantro and white onion.

A Mexican or Tex-Mex burrito, featuring a wrapped flour tortilla filled with such ingredients as beef, rice, beans, cheese, tomato, lettuce, and sour cream. Served in foil on several major platforms, suggesting a Mission burrito associated with San Francisco. Not to be confused with the Stuffed Flatbread.
A single tamale wrapped in a corn husk.

A flatbread, like pita, stuffed with lettuce, tomato, and/or meat. Resembles a doner kebab, falafel, shawarma, or gyro sandwich, popular in the Middle East and the Mediterranean. Some platforms have red onion and cucumber. Not to be confused with 🫓 Flatbread or 🌯 Burrito.

Brown spheres depicting falafel, a food popular in Middle Eastern and North African cuisine, typically made of mashed chickpeas or fava beans. Most platforms include three or more falafel with one piece split open to reveal a green center. Can be used to talk about falafel and possibly other round brown food items like meatballs.
An egg, displayed as a chicken egg with a white or light brown shell. Commonly used at Easter time. See also: 🍳 Cooking.
An egg with yolk frying in a skillet, as prepared sunny-side up. Though associated with breakfast, the emoji represents the general action of cooking and related concepts.

A flat, shallow, black pan with side handles, containing saffron-colored rice, vegetables, a leg of poultry, and/or shrimp and lemon slices. Commonly associated with paella, a traditional dish from Spain. May be used for eating, cooking, dining, and meals more generally.

A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Generally used for eating and cooking (“a meal”), and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe.
A red fondue pot. Most platforms show cheese fondue with fondue forks sticking out of the pot.
A bowl with a silver spoon inside, as used to eat cereal or soup. Bowl color varies across platforms, as do contents. Android depicts breakfast cereal, WhatsApp tomato soup; Apple’s is empty.
An undressed garden salad in a bowl with leafy-green lettuce and other ingredients such as tomato, red onion, and black olives. Commonly associated with healthy eating and living.
The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater.
A pale yellow stick of butter. Can be used to talk about cooking or eating. Might also be used in idioms or to reference something that is smooth.
A clear glass shaker of salt with a silver cap, as paired with pepper to season food when eating at a restaurant.
A can or tin of food, depicted as tomatoes or a generic green vegetable. May be also used to represent sauce or soup.
A Japanese bento, a lunch box divided into portions of rice, vegetables, and meat or seafood, such as sushi or fried shrimp.
A Japanese senbei, or rice cracker, wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed, a snack commonly enjoyed with green tea.
A Japanese onigiri, a cone-shaped ball of white rice, a snack wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed.
A bowl of steamed white rice, a staple component of cuisine throughout Asia. Bowl color varies across platforms, though is often white.
A plate of orange-brown curry with vegetables or meat, served with a mound of white rice. May represent kare-raisu, or Japanese curry, though commonly associated with India and other Asian cuisines.
A bowl of steaming-hot food. Depicted as Japanese ramen (noodles in broth) with chopsticks on most platforms, though it can represent a warm meal more generally.
A plate of Italian spaghetti with tomato sauce, as a bolognese, with a fork twirling its long, thin noodles. Garnished with a green herb, as parsley, on some platforms.

A sweet potato depicted with textured purple, orange, or brown skin and sliced in half to show its golden-brown flesh. Sometimes called a yam, though they are unrelated. Not to be confused with the Potato.

A skewer of three bites of Japanese oden, a winter dish made with fishcakes, tofu, konnyaku, and a variety of other ingredients, including boiled eggs. Often served as a stew or skewered and dipped into soy sauce. Resembles the Dango and may be used for other skewered foods (e.g., shish kebab, roasting marshmallows) or spears.

Japanese sushi, generally depicted as two pieces of raw pinkish-orange fish, as tuna or salmon, on white rice (nigiri). Some platforms show the cylindrical maki, a piece of seafood, vegetables, and white rice wrapped in seaweed (nori).
A prawn or shrimp breaded and deep-fried golden-brown. Known as ebi furai in Japan but commonly called shrimp tempura and served in a bento box. Not to be confused with the Shrimp.
A slice of Japanese narutomaki, a ridged fishcake of processed whitefish with an iconic pink swirl, often served in ramen or oden. Thanks to its distinct swirl, may be used for flair.

The round, golden-brown pastry of a Chinese mooncake, a traditional delicacy and lunar symbol of the Mid-Autumn Festival. Many platforms feature a design or character imprinted on the crust, and depict a slice cut out to show a brown paste with a duck egg yolk inside. Twitter displays the Chinese character for “fall/autumn” or “harvest” (秋) on top.

A Japanese sweet dumpling made from rice flour and served on a skewer. Depicted as a botchan dango, comprising a pink, white or light yellow, and green ball, as colored by red beans, egg, and green tea. Resembles the Oden and featured in the Moon Viewing Ceremony, used in the Japanese festival to celebrate the full moon.

A dumpling of dough and filling, as folded and pinched closed for steaming or frying. Associated with cuisines around the world, including China (jiaozi), Japan (gyoza or dango), Poland (pierogi), and Spain and Latin America (empanada). Facebook's design resembles a xiaolongbao, a Chinese soup dumpling.

A golden-brown, crescent-shaped, vanilla-flavored fortune cookie. Usually depicted with a strip of paper—on which a wise saying, lucky numbers, or Chinese vocabulary is written—peaking out of its hollow shell. Given at the end of meals at Chinese restaurants in the West.

A tall, folded, paper carton, usually white, as used for takeout/takeaway food at Western Chinese restaurants. Most platforms depict chopsticks inside its open lid, labeled with a red, multi-tiered, traditional Chinese building. Also called an oyster pail.
Half of an opened oyster shell with gray, pink, or orange flesh inside. Many platforms also include a pearl in the shell.

A swirl of soft-serve ice cream atop a wafer-style cone, white or cream-colored, as vanilla, on most platforms. Facebook’s design suggests strawberry. May be used more generally for ice cream, frozen yogurt, and frozen treats.
A mound of shaved ice (snow cone) served in a dessert bowl with a short spoon, flavored with a cherry-red syrup on many platforms. Associated with Hawaiian shave ice or Japanese kakigori.
One or more scoops of ice cream in a dessert bowl, variously topped with sprinkles, wafer rolls, or cherry and syrup. Flavors vary from vanilla, chocolate, and/or strawberry across platforms.
A chocolate-glazed donut (or doughnut) with rainbow sprinkles. WhatsApp features a pink glaze associated with The Simpsons. May resemble the Bagel at small sizes.
A golden-brown chocolate chip cookie or biscuit. Used to represent cookies or biscuits in general.

A frosted cake with lit candles, as presented for a birthday celebration. The style of cake widely varies across platforms. With white frosting and strawberries, Apple and Google’s designs suggest a Japanese Christmas cake. Other vendors depict a chocolate, pink, and/or sponge cake.
A slice of strawberry shortcake, layered with whipped cream and topped with a whole strawberry. Like the Birthday Cake, may be used to represent birthday celebrations or cake in general.

An individual cupcake in a liner topped with a swirl of frosting and sprinkles. The style of cupcake widely varies across platforms. The cake may be sponge or chocolate, the frosting pink or white, and the sprinkles rainbow or red.

A baked dish with a pastry crust, filled with sweet or savory ingredients. Appearance widely varies by platform. Apple depicts a whole pie in a tin, its crimped crust scored to let out steam. Google shows a slice of pumpkin pie as served at Thanksgiving, WhatsApp and Twitter a slice of cherry pie.
A block of dark chocolate, usually shown in a red foil wrapper peeled back to show squares of the candy. WhatsApp displays the wrapper in purple, a color commonly associated with Cadbury chocolate.

A small piece of candy wrapped in plastic or wax paper with twists on its ends. Shape and color vary widely by platform. Facebook’s design used to resemble a classic unwrapped red-and-white peppermint. May also be called sweets or lollies.
A colorful lollipop made of swirled hard candy attached to a stick. Colors vary by platform, though most designs show rainbow colors or pinks and reds.
A golden-yellow custard dessert, as a crème caramel or flan, topped with a layer of caramel. Shown on a plate, molded in a ramekin-shape and often in a pool of caramel sauce.
A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears. Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel.

A bottle of milk or formula, as or fed to a baby, with a bluish cap and rubber nipple or teat. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle, and filled to various levels, sometimes showing fill lines. Often used for newborns and childrearing. See also Breast-Feeding.
A tall glass of white milk, as from a cow but also other mammals, nuts, or plants. Most platforms depict a glass filled near to the brim, but some show a glass half-full—or half-empty.
A cup of a steaming-hot beverage, usually taken as coffee or tea. Sometimes shown on a saucer. Samsung features a foamy-white tulip latte art design.
A classic teapot with a wide bulbous body, a spout, a handle, and a lid. Can be used to talk about tea, tea time, or warm beverages in general.

A cup of green tea, as the minty-colored Japanese matcha, usually shown on a wooden mat. Matcha is traditionally served in a small bowl that resembles a cup without a handle. Often taken as a bowl of soup, such as a split pea.

Japanese sake, an alcoholic beverage made from rice. Shown as a sake set with a carafe (tokkuri) and drinking cup (choko). Most platforms show a cream colored sake set with a blue or red stripe motif. Samsung's design used to show the Japanese script for 'sake' in red along the side of the carafe.

A green bottle of champagne or sparkling wine with label, its cork popping to shoot out its bubbly contents. Used for a range of celebratory occasions, such as New Year's Eve, birthdays, weddings, or other life accomplishments.
Red wine served in a stemmed glass. Google previously displayed an orange-colored drink that resembled cognac.
A stemmed glass with a cone-shaped bowl, used for serving cocktails. Depicted as a martini garnished with an olive. Might be gin or vodka, shaken or stirred. See also Tropical Drink.

A sunset-orange-colored tropical beverage in a stemmed glass, as a rum punch or mai tai. Served with a straw and fruit garnish. Many platforms include a cocktail umbrella, hence umbrella drink. Samsung previously featured an electric-blue concoction. See also Cocktail Glass.
A beer, as a golden-colored lager, in a frosty mug. Depicted with a frothy head spilling over the brim. Clinking Beer Mugs is a variation that displays two such beer mugs.

Two frosty mugs of beer with frothy heads being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Several platforms include stylized lines to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Glasses.

Two flutes of champagne or sparkling wine being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Samsung’s design suggests two glasses of white wine. Some platforms include stylized links to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Beer Mugs—and Bottle With Popping Cork for a refill.

A short, flat glass, as used for brown liquors like whiskey or Scotch whisky. Apple and WhatsApp serve theirs neat, while other platforms include ice ("on the rocks"). Samsung's glass features the faint initials ONI, an apparent in-company easter egg.

A drinking cup with a straw. Depicted on many platforms as a disposable cup with a lid and bendy straw, as used to serve soft drinks at fast-food restaurants. May be used for a range of non-alcoholic beverages, including milkshakes, smoothies, juice, and to-go beverages.
Bubble tea is a tea-based drink invented in Taiwan which typically contain tea, flavored milk, and sugar. Commonly served with tapioca pearls, also known as boba, in a plastic cup with a wide straw.

Originally proposed as Juice, this emoji can be used to talk about juice or other liquids that come in boxes with straws. It can also be used metaphorically to talk about power, energy, respect, or an elusive quality that makes someone special.
Mate is a caffeinated beverage popular in many South American countries. Green in color (from a key ingredient: the dried leaves of yerba mate) and consumed via a metal straw.
A blue cube of ice. Can be used to talk about ice or cold temperatures in general. This emoji can also be used metaphorically to talk about something that is cool or chill.

A pair of equal-length chopsticks, an eating utensil used throughout East Asia. Design and color vary widely by platform, though often red or wood-colored and with tips angled together. Featured in many platforms' Steaming Bowl of Food and Takeout Box. A counterpart to utensils such as Fork and Knife and Spoon.
A silver fork and knife on either side of a white plate, as set for dinner or another meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon.
A silver fork to the left of a knife, silverware or cutlery used to eat a meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon or used with Fork and Knife With Plate.

A silver spoon, as used to eat soup, cereal, or ice cream as well as serve food or stir drinks. Positioned at various angles across platforms. May be paired with Fork and Knife, Fork and Knife With Plate, and Bowl With Spoon.
A person wearing a suit, hovering above the ground with a shadow displayed beneath them. Generally shown wearing a fedora or similar style of hat.

A rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet and/or rope. The Emojipedia Sample image was created with assistance from World Champion Rock Climber Sasha DiGiulian.
A male rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.
A female rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.
A person shown in the sport of fencing, with a Rapier-style sword, mask, and protective clothing.

A jockey riding a horse in a horse race. Shown riding to the left of screen on all major platforms. Emoji modifiers change the skin tone of the jockey on some platforms, which can be difficult to discern at small sizes.
A person downhill-skiiing. Displayed with poles and skis, generally wearing a mask.
A person snowboarding downhill at a ski resort. Wearing clothing designed for cold climates.
A person swinging a golf club, attempting to hit a golf ball toward the flag on the green.
The male version of the 🏌 Golfer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🏌 Golfer emoji.
A person on a surfboard, riding on a wave in the ocean. Wears a wetsuit or board shorts in most versions.
The male version of the 🏄 Surfer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🏄 Surfer emoji.
A small rowboat suitable for a small number of people. Couples or families sometimes hire these as an activity on calm waters.
The male version of the 🚣 Rowboat emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🚣 Rowboat emoji.
A person swimming in a pool, the ocean, or another body of water. Lacked goggles on prior versions of iOS.
The male version of the 🏊 Swimmer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🏊 Swimmer emoji.
A person with a ball, which is generally displayed as a basketballer running and dribbling (bouncing) the basketball.
The male version of the ⛹ Person With Ball emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the ⛹ Person With Ball emoji.
A person lifting a barbell loaded with weights above their head.
The male version of the 🏋 Weight Lifter emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🏋 Weight Lifter emoji.
A person riding a bicycle for leisure, sport or transport. Intended to be gender-neutral.
The male version of the 🚴 Bicyclist emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🚴 Bicyclist emoji.
A person (cyclist) who rides a mountain bike: a type of off-road bicycle. Intended to be gender-neutral.
The male version of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The female version of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist emoji.
A person doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics.

The Man Cartwheeling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤸 Person Cartwheeling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Woman Cartwheeling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤸 Person Cartwheeling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.
Two people in the sport of wrestling.

The Men Wrestling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤼 People Wrestling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Women Wrestling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤼 People Wrestling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.
A person shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo.

The Man Playing Water Polo emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤽 Person Playing Water Polo, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Woman Playing Water Polo emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤽 Person Playing Water Polo, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Person Playing Handball was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Handball”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

The Man Playing Handball emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤾 Person Playing Handball, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Woman Playing Handball emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤾 Person Playing Handball, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.
A person juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji generally has the appearance of a man, and wears a hat on most major platforms.

The Man Juggling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤹 Person Juggling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Woman Juggling emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🤹 Person Juggling, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Person in Lotus Position was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

The Man in Lotus Position emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🧘 Person in Lotus Position, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂️ Male Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

The Woman in Lotus Position emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🧘 Person in Lotus Position, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀️ Female Sign.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.
A circular ‘big top’ circus tent, with a triangle flag on top.
A skateboard emoji, shown on some platforms from the top and others showing the under-side of the board.
A single vibrantly colored roller skate. Colors and styles vary across platform.

Canoe was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.
An awareness ribbon, worn to show support of a cause or group.
A ticket or tickets to an event that may say "Admit One" on the front. Shown in pink or yellow on most platforms.
A paper ticket, which may be for a theatre show, sporting event, or other ticketed performance. Shown in blue, yellow or grey on most platforms.
A ribbon and medallion generally awarded to a person in the military for heroic acts.
A trophy given as an recognition of achievement, usually in sports. The trophy emoji is a gold cup, with a engraving on the bottom detailing the award.
A gold medal, given to a person who has won a sporting event, such as a race. Not to be confused with the military medal emoji.

1st Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “First Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

2nd Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Second Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

3rd Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Third Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.
A round, black and white ball used in the game of soccer, which is known as football in much of the world. See also: emojis for the World Cup.
A white baseball, with regulation red stitching. Used in the game of the same name, baseball.
A softball, which is differentiated from a baseball by size (it is larger, though hard to tell in emoji form) and color (yellow, not white).
An orange-colored basketball displayed with a hoop. Many versions of this emoji omit the hoop, and display only the basketball.
A volleyball emoji, showing the round ball used in the sport. Played as part of the Summer Olympic Games.
The oval ball used in the game of American football, known as gridiron in some countries.
The oval-shaped ball used in the game of rugby. Varies slightly in shape in the two main versions of the game: rugby union and rugby league.
A tennis racket (racquet) with a tennis ball. Only a ball is shown on Apple, LG, Twitter, Facebook, and Mozilla platforms.
A flying disc, more commonly known as a frisbee. Used in the sport of Ultimate or disc golf.
Ten-pin bowling emoji, showing a bowling ball and pins.
A cricket bat, with a cricket ball also shown. May be displayed with a wicket present.
A hockey stick and ball, used in the sport of field hockey. Not to be confused with the ice hockey stick and puck.
A hockey stick and puck, used in the sport of ice hockey. Not to be confused with the field hockey stick and ball.

Lacrosse was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Lacrosse Stick and Ball”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.
A paddle and ping pong ball used in the sport of table tennis.

Badminton was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Badminton Racquet and Shuttlecock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
A padded boxing glove, used in the sport of boxing. Usually red.
A white uniform used in marital arts such as judo or karate. Held together using a material belt. Known as keikogi in Japanese.

Goal Net was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.
A red, triangular flag shown sitting in the hole of a golf course green. Some versions of this emoji also include golf balls.
A single ice skate used for ice skating. Shown in white and facing right on most platforms.
A fishing rod (pole) with a fish caught on the end.
A singlet or running shirt. Shown with a sash.
A pair of skis which are shown on some platforms alongside ski poles and/or ski boots. The color and design of the skis varies by platform, with some versions also showing the skis moving at speed.
A sled, otherwise known as a toboggan or sledge.

Curling Stone was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.
A dart board with dart hitting the center / bullseye region.
The game of billiards, of which pool is a common version. This emoji displays the black 8 ball on most platforms, which looks similar to the Magic 8-Ball toy.
A video game emoji, shown on major platforms as a console gamepad with D-pad, joysticks, and buttons.
A gambling machine generally found in casinos. Shows three wheels with a lever to the side. Most platforms display three 7 digits on this emoji.
A six-sided die, used in a range of board and turn-based games. Commonly called dice which refers to the plural of die.

Puzzle Piece was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Jigsaw Puzzle Piece”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

Chess Pawn was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Chess Pawn”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.
Two masks often used on maps to indicate a theatre, these originate in Greek Theatre as masks of tragedy and comedy.
A palette used by an artist when painting, to store and mix paint colors.
A spool of thread, as used for sewing. Thread color varies across platforms, though often depicted in red or blue and on a wooden spool. Sometimes shown with an end unraveling.

A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf. Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball.
A staff (or stave) showing a treble clef and five horizontal lines.
A microphone, used to amplify a person’s voice when speaking or singing. Shown with music notes on most platforms, implying it to be used for a singer / singing.
Headphones, used to listen to music or other forms audio, such as podcasts. Most platforms display this emoji with large over-ear headphones in shades of black, blue, and gray.

Saxophone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Accordion was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.
A guitar, which most platforms display as a red electric guitar.
A small section of a music keyboard, which differs from a computer keyboard.
A trumpet, a brass instrument played in jazz bands.
A violin emoji. Sometimes used in the context of the world’s smallest violin.
A drum shown with drumsticks. A percussion instrument which is likely to be displayed as a snare drum.music, instrument,

Long Drum was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.
A board which contains the scene name, number, and film. A person ‘claps’ the board shut at the top while saying “Action” or “Cut” to indicate the start and stop of a scene that is being filmed.
A bow and arrow used in the sport of archery. May also be used by cupid.
A small rowboat suitable for a small number of people. Couples or families sometimes hire these as an activity on calm waters.
Shows a map of the country of Japan, which is the only country to have its own emoji map. Other countries can be found on the various globe emojis, or the world map emoji.
A mountain with snow resting at higher altitudes. Similar in appearance to the Mount Fuji emoji.
A mountain shown with two peaks and blue sky. Similar to the snow capped mountain emoji.
A volcano, erupting with smoke and lava.
Mount Fuji (called Fuji-san in Japan) is the largest mountain in Japan. Often seen with snow on the peak in colder months of the year.
A campsite featuring a tent and a tree, and perhaps a campfire. Similar to the tent emoji.
A beach showing sand, and an umbrella for protection from the sun.

Desert was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Desert Island was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
A national park, generally displayed with mountains, a river or stream, and trees.
A large capacity stadium, featuring a large amount of seating for sporting fans, or people attending other shows hosted by the stadium.
A building shown with columns in a classical style, sometimes used to represent a courthouse, town hall, post office or stock exchange.
A construction site generally depicted as a tower crane shown lifting steel or other building materials.
A round hut with a thatched roof. Used to talk about huts, cottages, yurts, or homes in general.
Multiple houses.
A house which is unoccupied, and has become derelict. In a state of disrepair.
A house, otherwise known as a home when someone is living in it. Suitable for a couple or larger family, other perhaps housemates.
A suburban-looking house, with a tree, flower, or shrubs around it in the garden.
A generic, high-rise office building. Generally found in cities, and most active during business hours.
A Japanese post office, featuring the テ Japanese postal mark on the front of the building (or showing this mark instead of the building in Microsoft’s artwork).
A European-style post office. A postal horn can be seen on the front, which is commonly found in the logos of European Postal Services.
A place where people are taken to receive medical care. This hospital has a large red cross on the front, often used as a symbol for health care.
A retail bank branch, where people can perform money-related tasks. Also a common location to find an ATM.
A hotel building, displayed on most platforms as a building with many windows and a letter H on the front.
A love hotel is a hotel that can be hired by the hour instead of as accommodation for the evening.
A shop that is generally open for longer hours than a regular supermarket, sometimes 24 hours per day.
A school building with multiple storeys, and a clock on the front. A place that children, or teenagers attend for their education.
A large department store, selling a range of products to the general public. Shown as a large building with a billboard on most platforms, or as a shopping bag on Windows.
An industrial factory, with flue-gas stacks releasing exhaust into the air.
A traditional Japanese Castle, usually made from stone and wood.
A castle, in a style that can be found in France and other parts of Europe.
An emoji to depict a wedding, displayed by most vendors as a Christian church and love hearts. Some platforms display a cross or bell on the building.
The Tokyo Tower is the second-tallest building in Japan, located in Minato, Tokyo.
The Statue of Liberty, often used as a depiction of New York City.
A church building, generally associated with Christian denominations. In addition quiet prayer, churches hold regular worship services, weddings, baptisms and funerals.
A mosque building, a place of worship for followers of Islam. Shown with a domed roof and a minaret.
A Hindu temple or mandir; a place of worship for followers of Hinduism. Depicted on most platforms as a red, orange, or golden building with a tall spire.
A synague; a place of worship for followers of Judaism. Displayed with a Star of David on the front.

A shrine used for the Japanese Shinto religion. This emoji generally displays the torii, which is the gate to the Shinto Shrine. The torii is generally a red colored structure, with a curved roof section above two posts.
A cube-shaped building located at the centre of the Al-Masjid al-Haram Mosque in Mecca.
A water fountain, found in a park or other public space. Used for decorative purposes. A variety of styles of fountain are shown across different platforms.
A tent, used for protection from wind and rain when camping. Often shown at night time, under stars.
Foggy weather displayed as fog covering a bridge or cityscape, depending on the platform. For platforms that show a bridge, the red Golden Gate Bridge is generally displayed.
A night sky with stars, depicted on major platforms as a cityscape at night.

Cityscape was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
The sun rising over a mountain range, early in the morning.
A sun rising, early in the morning. Can be difficult to distinguish from a sunset in some versions of this artwork.
A view of city buildings as the last light disappears from the sky. An orange (or blue) glow lingers, before the stars of the night sky become visible.
A beautiful view, featuring an orange sky, with the sun setting over the buildings of a city skyline.
A lit-up bridge, shown at night.
A wooden painted horse, found on the carousel at a carnival. Faces to the left-of screen.
A large rotating wheel, often found at a carnival or fair.
A roller coaster in a theme park going down a dip in the ride. Three carriages can be seen with two people in each red carriage.
A steam train, powered by coal or wood. An early type of locomotive, now mostly replaced by electric or diesel trains.

A railway (railroad) car (carriage) that is generally pulled along a railway line by a locomotive. Shown with a pantograph above the carriage on many platforms which makes it look more like a tram car.
A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed.
A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. Also features a streamlined bullet nose, often used in reference to the Shinkansen in Japan.
A train, of no specified type. Due to the presence of a steam train and fast train emoji, this is likely to be a regular electrified or diesel passenger train.
A metro: frequent underground train found in built-up areas with high populations.
A form of public transport similar to a tram, but running on a track or network separated from cars and other types of traffic.
A station, presumed to be a train station. Displays a train alongside a platform, where passengers can board.
A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
Similar to a train, but running on a single track. Monorails are often found at theme parks, or other tourist destinations.
A train and railway in the mountains. Displayed as a funicular in Microsoft’s artwork, or a regular train on other platforms.
A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
A bus used for public transport in cities and towns. Could also be used as a school bus.
The front of a bus, showing the windscreen, as well as wing mirrors in some versions of this emoji.
A type of bus that uses overhead electrical wires for power. Appears similar to a cross between a bus and a tram car.
A small bus or minivan designed to carry fewer people than a full-sized bus. Displayed in white on most platforms (green on Facebook).
An ambulance, used to transport patients between their home and the hospital.
A red fire truck, an essential part of emergency services along with a police car or ambulance.
A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top.
A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top.
A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the side, as opposed to the oncoming taxi emoji.
A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the front, as opposed to the taxi emoji which displays the side of the vehicle.
A car shown from the side, facing right-to-left. Appears as a red car on most platforms (which goes faster), except on Android where this displays as a silver car (previously blue).
A car being shown from the front. The windscreen and hood (bonnet in British English) of the car can be seen facing forward.
A blue or green Sport Utility Vehicle or station wagon, often with a spare tire on the back. Commonly used as a generic blue or green car.
A red or turquoise pickup truck. Used to talk about trucks or modes of transportation in general.

Delivery Truck was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Articulated Lorry was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
A tractor, may be used by a farmer or other occupation on the land.
A racing car which appears as a formula one vehicle or rally car on most platforms. Generally displayed in red.
A motorcycle, otherwise known as a motorbike used for sport/racing purposes. For a transport-based motorcycle, use a motor scooter.
A motor scooter, which may be displayed as any type of motorbike with or without a step-through frame. Distinct from the racing motorcycle, which is used for sport, not transport.

An auto rickshaw, often referred to as a tuk tuk. This motorized version of a cycle rickshaw is used for transport in many regions of the world. Generally this emoji has three wheels and open sides without doors.
A bicycle, sometimes called a push bike, used for transport or sport.
A non-motorized scooter, with two wheels and handles.
A sign indicating the location of a bus stop by the side of a road.
A wide road shown from a first person perspective. Apple's artwork displays a road sign to Curpertino.

Railway Track was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
A fuel pump, used to fill up a vehicle with gas / petrol.
A revolving red light seen on top of a police car. Often used in emergency circumstances in addition to a siren making a loud warning sound.
A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. Less common than the vertical traffic light.
A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. More common than the horizontal traffic light.

A sign used to indicate roadwork or construction. Generally shown as yellow and black diagonal stripes, and often used to physically block access to a road or area. May be used to imply a website or project in progress or under construction.
A metal device, dropped out of a boat to prevent it drifting away from the current location.
A sailboat, otherwise known as a sailing boat or yacht.  Uses wind as the source of propulsion to move around a body of water.
A motorized speedboat used for recreation on lakes, or other bodies of water.

Passenger Ship was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Ferry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Motor Boat was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
A large ship, used for transport of people or cargo across the ocean. May be a cruise ship, commonly found around tropical locations.
Used either as a literal airplane, to represent an overseas vacation, or sometimes as a proxy for airplane mode on a phone or tablet.
A light aircraft which is shown with propellers on some platforms.
A plane taking off from a runway. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane elevated.
A plane approaching a runway for landing. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane facing toward the ground in a position that may result in a crash if attempted in the real world.
An open parachute floating through the air with a human steering. Most platforms feature a ram-air design. Colors vary across platforms.
A seat, which could refer to any form of place to sit, with the distinction that a seat is generally fixed, and is not a chair which can be moved.
A helicopter, which can hover in the air. Often seen in emergency circumstances such as transporting patients to a hospital, or for police or fire-fighting activity.
Similar to a monorail, a suspension railway is elevated, but the vehicle is suspended under the track.

Mountain Cableway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
An Aerial Tramway, most commonly seen at ski resorts, for transport between locations on a mountain. Can also be used as a tourist attraction, or as a form of public transport.
A satellite which orbits the earth, and is generally used for communications, weather, and GPS.
A rocket being propelled into space. Sometimes used to indicate a fast increase, for instance when referring to stocks going to the moon 🚀 (rising quickly in price).
A flying saucer, sometimes referred to as an Unidentified Flying Object (UFO). Shown on some platforms with an alien at the controls and/or a beam of light emitting from the base.
A ringed planet that appears with various number of rings, tilt angles, and colors across platforms. This vaguely Saturn-like orb was proposed as a stand-alone planet emoji to represent all planets.

A stylized representation of a shooting star, a small, fast meteor that burns up in the atmosphere. Generally depicted as a gold, five-point star trailing yellow motion lines against a night sky, as if moving down to the left.
The Milky Way – a galaxy of billions of stars that includes our own solar system and planet earth.
A large, open umbrella, as provides shade at a beach or patio. Generally depicted as a striped umbrella inserted into a patch of sand and tilted to the right.
Firework emoji, showing a explosion of colored light in the night sky, used for any number of celebrations such as New Year's Eve.
A  sparkler: a form of hand-held firework often used at parties and celebrations. The sparkler is lit at one end, and held at the other.
Moon Viewing Ceremonies (called Tsukimi in Japan) are held each year in autumn to celebrate the full moon and waxing moon in Japan.

A banded stack of yen banknotes, the paper currency of Japan. Color and detail vary across platforms, but usually shown in green, yellow, or pink with the yen symbol, ¥. Commonly used for various content concerning money and wealth, not restricted to Japan.

Cash money! A banded stack of U.S. dollar banknotes, the paper currency of the United States of America. Green hue and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the dollar sign, $. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.S.

A banded stack of euro banknotes, the paper currency of the European Union (EU). Color and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the euro sign, €. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the EU.

Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom (England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and Scotland). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple £20 notes with the pound sign, £.
A moai, one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left.
A person checking passports at an international border.
A customs officer inspecting luggage. May be shown on signage at airports or other border crossings.

Baggage Claim was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
An icon representing a place to leave luggage. Most commonly found at Japanese train stations to signify coin lockers where bags can be stored for a daily fee.

The back of an envelope, generally shown in white and sealed with a red heart. Represents a love letter or note, valentine, or affectionate greeting card. Commonly used to convey various feelings or messages of love and happiness.
A round, black, cartoon-styled hole, as a manhole or a hole (cup) in golf. May be used to represent various types of literal or figurative holes, e.g., black holes, rabbit holes.
A cartoon-styled bomb, depicted as a black ball with a burning fuse.

A gender-unspecified person taking a soothing bath in a white tub with a shower head. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally. May also represent relaxation and self-care.

A bed with a gender-unspecified person sleeping in it, as at a house, hotel, hostel, or other sleeping accommodation. Used especially for various content concerning sleeping as well as beds, furniture, housing, relaxing, and other bedroom activities.
A knife with a long steel blade, as a chef uses to slice meat or vegetables. Depicted with a black or brown handle and positioned at a 45° angle, often with its point at the lower right.
A tall, ceramic jar with two handles and a narrow neck and foot. Represents an amphora, as used by ancient Greeks and Romans to hold water and wine.
A rectangular map of the world. Generally depicted as a paper map creased at its folds, Earth’s surface shown in green on blue ocean.

A magnetic compass, as used for navigation. Generally depicted in a silver or gold case with a compass rose and a red-tipped needle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling and exploring as well as metaphorical compasses (e.g., moral compass).
A red brick or bricks. Depicted in a loose stack, a single object with holes, or as built into wall, as of a house, school, or other structure.
A pole spiraled with red, white, and blue stripes, as spins out front of a barbershop. Commonly used for various content concerning haircutting and hairstyling.

A manual wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol, which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also 👩‍🦽Woman in Manual Wheelchair or 👨‍🦽Man in Manual Wheelchair.

A motorized wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also 👩‍🦼Woman in Motorized Wheelchair or 👨‍🦼Man in Motorized Wheelchair.

A barrel for transporting bulk liquids, such as oil. Generally depicted as a red or blue metal drum with holes or a stopper on its lid. Commonly used for various content concerning petroleum or hazardous waste.

Ding! A call bell, as pressed at a front desk or reception to alert staff for service, such as from a concierge or bellhop (porter) to carry luggage at a hotel. Generally depicted as a golden bell on a wooden stand.

A suitcase or bag, as used for traveling. Most platforms depict gray or blue rolling luggage with an extended handle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling or taking trips, whether for business or leisure.
A classic hourglass, all of its sand having flowed into the bottom bulb. Indicates time has passed. Color varies across platforms.
A classic hourglass, its sand still flowing from the top to bottom bulb. Indicates time is still passing—but life is short. Color varies across platforms.
A wristwatch, as used for telling time. Appearance varies across platforms, but widely depicted as an analog timepiece with a white face and brown or black straps.

A timepiece set in advance to startle a person awake at the designated time with its two bells. That is, before hitting snooze. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted as a classic, wind-up, bedside alarm clock, often red in color.
An analog, handheld timepiece used to measure elapsed time, as for athletic sprints. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted with two or more control buttons on its top.

Time’s up! A timer set to count down and sound an alarm after a designated amount of time, as used in the kitchen. Appearance varies by platform. Commonly used for various content concerning time, including countdowns and deadlines.
An antique-styled mantel clock with a flat base and rounded case, as made of wood and brass and placed above a fireplace.

A liquid-in-glass thermometer, as used to measure temperature. Depicted at various angles with a red liquid risen from the bulb to various levels on the scale. Commonly used for content concerning high temperatures, including warm weather, illness (having a fever), and various slang senses of hot.
A large, open umbrella, as provides shade at a beach or patio. Generally depicted as a striped umbrella inserted into a patch of sand and tilted to the right.
A firecracker, as lit on Chinese New Year, New Year's Eve, or Independence Day. Depicted as a red tube with a burning fuse, sometimes lined with gold rings at its top and base.
A balloon on a string, as decorates a birthday party. Generally depicted in red, though WhatsApp’s is pink and Google’s orangish-red.

A party popper, as explodes in a shower of confetti and streamers at a celebration. Generally depicted as a gold party hat, striped on some platforms, at a 45° angle, with multicolored confetti and streamers coming from its opening at the upper right. Twitter’s cone is red.
A golden ball, split in two halves in a shower of multicolored confetti and streamers.
Ornamental Japanese Emperor and Empress dolls, as displayed in celebration of Hinamatsuri on March 3 in Japan (Girls’ or Dolls’ Day).
Japanese koinobori, decorative, carp-shaped windsocks flown in celebration of Children’s Day on May 5 in Japan. Generally depicted as a blue and red stylized carp fish on a golden pole.
A Japanese wind chime. Depicted as a glass bell with a strip of paper suspended from its clapper, often decorated with cherry blossom-like flowers.
A red envelope, as gifted with money on Chinese New Year or on other joyous occasions, such as weddings, in Chinese and some other Asian cultures around the world.
A pink or red ribbon, as tied into a bow on a gift or woman's hat.
A present or gift in a box tied with a bow, as given on a birthday or Christmas. Box and ribbon color vary across platforms, but commonly depicted as a gold box with a lid wrapped with a red ribbon.
A diving mask with a snorkel, used for scuba diving or other underwater activities. Colors vary across platforms.
A round yo-yo with its string coming out. It appears in various colors and designs across platforms.
A diamond-shaped kite with a tail. This emoji appears in various colors across platforms.
A crystal ball, as a fortune teller or clairvoyant gazes into to tell the future. Depicted as a sparkling, purple or blue crystal orb resting on a stand.

A wand with sparkles (✨magic✨) coming out of its end. Most platforms show a classic magician-style magic wand that's black with white tips. WhatsApp shows a golden magic wand tipped with a star, similar to the wand that Glenda the Good Witch uses in the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz.

A nazar, an eye-shaped amulet believed to protect against the evil eye, especially in Turkish culture. Depicted as a rich blue, circular bead with a black dot in the center ringed with white and light blue, resembling an eye.
A joystick, as used in playing classic arcade, computer, or video games. Generally depicted with a black base, red-knobbed control stick, and one or more red buttons.
A classic teddy bear, as snuggled by a child when going to sleep.
A colorful decorated container that comes in many shapes, a piñata is filled with candy or toys. Hit to break open for celebrations such as Cinco de Mayo, this is generally associated with Mexico.

Nesting Dolls was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

A framed picture of a painting or photograph, as displayed in a gallery or on a household wall. Vendors feature various scenes, though generally a lush, sunny landscape of hills and mountains, in a gold frame.
A spool of thread, as used for sewing. Thread color varies across platforms, though often depicted in red or blue and on a wooden spool. Sometimes shown with an end unraveling.

Sewing Needle was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf. Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball.

Knot was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

Two colorful shopping bags, as contain consumer items bought at a department store. Depicted as gift bags in various bright colors, patterns, sizes, and positions across platforms. Apple's design, for instance, features a pink bag with light-pink dots in front of a gold bag with yellow stripes.
A string of beads, as used in prayer or meditation in many religious traditions. Generally depicted as red, wooden beads with a gold, decorative center bead and tassel.
A jewel or gem, as set into a ring. Depicted in the shape of a classic diamond but in the bright blue color of an aquamarine.

A postal horn (post horn). Depicted as a coiled, valveless, brass horn, like a bugle or trumpet, with two red tassels. Sometimes used to mark announcements as well as for various content concerning brass instruments, music, or mail.
A microphone, as used for radio broadcasting or studio recording. Most platforms depict a vintage, silver microphone, like the Shure Unidyne 55.
A level slider, as adjusts volume on a mixing console. Most platforms depict a silver and black channel fader with scale markings, set to various levels. Apple and Google's go up to eleven.
Four control knobs, as adjust audio levels on a mixing console. Generally depicted as a silver square with black knobs, turned to various levels as indicated by white pointers and scale markings.
A classic portable radio, as used to listen to music, news, or sports. Depicted in various colors and styles with a speaker, antenna, dial, and knobs.
A banjo with a round body and a long neck. Used to talk about banjos or music in general.

A mobile phone (cell phone), as used to text, check social media, or take selfies. Depicted as a black or gray smartphone with a generic blue screen or multicolored app icons. Commonly used for various content concerning mobile phones, technology, and communication.

A mobile phone (cell phone) with a rightward arrow pointed at it from the left. Intended to indicate an incoming call or message, but used to represent mobile phones, technology, and communication more generally.
A classic telephone, as a landline home phone. Most platforms depict a red, push-button phone with the handset on the base. Some platforms feature designs with rotary dials.
The handset of a traditional telephone, with speaker and microphone. Generally depicted in black at a 45° angle.

A pager, as worn on the waist to alert a person to a phone call or short text message. Popular in the 1980–90s before mobile phones, though still used by some medical and emergency personnel. Very occasionally used to represent alerts, digital communication, or nostalgia for old technology.

A fax machine, as scans and transmits documents over a telephone line. Common in the 1980–90s before the internet. Depicted as a white or black machine with a telephone handset, keypad, display screen, and paper in its tray.

An electric battery, as used to power such devices as a flashlight. Generally depicted as an upright, green cylinder, as a AA or D cell, with white indicators for its positive (facing up) and negative terminals.
An electric plug, as inserted into socket to power a device. Depicted as a black, two-pronged plug at various angles at the end of a cable. Prongs are silver or gold.
A laptop personal computer. Depicted as a black or gray device, opened to show a dark or blue screen, keyboard, and touchpad.
A desktop personal computer. Generally depicted as a black or gray monitor with a dark or blue screen.

A computer printer, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. May be used for various content concerning printing, including as a Print icon, as well as for office work and technology more generally.
A keyboard, as used to type on a computer. Generally depicted as a gray device with white or black keys. Used for various content concerning computers, typing, and writing.
A mouse, as used to control a cursor on a computer. Generally depicted as a white or gray, cordless device with a scroll wheel between left- and right-click buttons.

A trackball, as rotated to control a cursor on a computer. An alternative or supplement to a computer mouse or touchpad. Generally depicted as a cordless device with a blue or red ball in a cylindrical, black or gray socket.
A minidisc, depicted as a small, silver or gold optical disc housed in a square cartridge, its shutter positioned to the right.

A 3.5-inch floppy disk, a data storage format popular in the 1980–90s but largely preserved as a Save icon in computer programs. Shown with its silver shutter positioned up and in a black housing with a white label, accented with blue or red.

A silver optical disc, as a CD or DVD, used to play music or movies before the rise of streaming technology. Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.
A digital versatile disc (DVD), a type of optical disc used to play movies before the rise of streaming technology. Generally depicted in gold, though Facebook’s is bluish gray, as a Blu-ray.
An abacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. Depicted as a wooden frame with four or more rows or columns of variously positioned and colored beads.
A classic movie camera. Depicted as a black camera with two mounted reels of film, viewfinder, and lens pointed left or right.
A strip of film, as used in a movie camera or photography. Generally depicted as several horizontal frames of unexposed film with black trim and perforations.
A classic film projector, as projects film onto a screen for viewing. Generally depicted as a black or gray projector with two mounted reels and lens pointed right.
A classic television set, as people watched before streaming on flatscreens. Depicted in various colors and styles with a screen, knobs, and, on many platforms, rabbit-ear antennae.
A classic camera, as an SLR used to take pictures before camera phones. Generally depicted with a black and silver casing with lens and operating controls.
A classic camera, shown with its flash going off, as to illuminate a darker scene. Vendors implement the same design as 📷 Camera with a burst of light, often resembling 💥 Collision.
A video camera, as a camcorder used to film home videos in the 1980–90s. Generally depicted as a gray or black video camera with viewfinder, control buttons, and lens pointed left.
A videotape cassette, as a VHS tape used to watch movies or record TV on VCRs before DVDs , DVRs, and streaming. Generally depicted as a black cassette with a white label between its reels.

A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed left. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper left.

A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed right. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper right.
A burning candle, as lit when taking a bath or the power is out. Depicted as a white, pillar-shaped candle with a flame and wax dripping down its sides.
A light bulb, as screwed into a lamp to light a room. Depicted as an incandescent bulb with a silver base, often shown with filament and a soft, yellow-white glow.

An everyday flashlight (electric torch), as used when the power goes out, camping, or telling scary stories. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a gray and black device with a switch, shown illuminated on many platforms.
A red paper lantern, as hangs outside an izakaya, a Japanese bar that serves drinks and casual food. Generally depicted as cylindrical with a black top and base and soft, orange glow.
A lamp made of brass or clay, displayed with a lit wick leading into oil or ghee.

A closed, hardcover notebook, as used for journaling or sketching. Appearance varies across platforms, with most designs featuring relatively plain covers. Commonly used for content concerning writing and schooling.
A closed, hardcover book depicted with a red cover on most platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a red accent color.
An open, hardcover book, depicted with a blue cover on most platforms. Some platforms include a bookmark. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling.
A closed, green, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a green accent color.
A closed, blue, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a blue accent color.
A closed, orange, hardcover book—similar to the Emojipedia logo 📙😃. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as an orange accent color.

A loose stack of three of more different-colored, hardcover books. Commonly used for various content concerning reading and schooling. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but often shown with red, green, and blue covers.
A dark-colored, hardcover notebook, as used to write or take notes in school. Commonly used for various content concerning writing and schooling.
A spiral-bound, yellow, hardcover notebook. Intended to depict a financial ledger, as used in accounting.
A white piece of paper, curled up at the bottom to the left or right, with text printed on it, as a business letter. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
An ancient scroll, unrolled to reveal text on papyrus or parchment paper. May be used to represent the study of history or official documents, such as a diploma.

A white piece of paper, its top right corner curled or dog-eared, with text printed on it, as a business letter or icon for a document on a computer. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
The front page of a newspaper, as people once read the news before the internet. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.
A newspaper rolled up and bound, as for delivery to a house. Generally positioned at a 45° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.
Sheets of white, printed paper with variously colored tabs to bookmark important sections or indicate signature lines. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

A bookmark, as used to mark one's place in a book. May also represent bookmarks on an internet browser. Appearance varies across platforms, but generally depicted at a 45° angle as a thin, white or red strip with a decorative tie and design, such as flower or star.
A light-brown or yellow rectangular tag, as labelled and attached to a key. Depicted at various angles punched with a hole, generally with a metal ring or loop of string.
A bag full of money. Depicted as a sack, usually tan, tied off and displaying a dollar sign. May be filled with coins, as most platforms show a rounded bag.
A coin, shown in silver or gold. Appearance varies by platform, with Google and Twitter showing a 🏛️ Classical Building, while Samsung shows the number one, similar to a 🥇 1st Place Medal.

A banded stack of yen banknotes, the paper currency of Japan. Color and detail vary across platforms, but usually shown in green, yellow, or pink with the yen symbol, ¥. Commonly used for various content concerning money and wealth, not restricted to Japan.

Cash money! A banded stack of U.S. dollar banknotes, the paper currency of the United States of America. Green hue and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the dollar sign, $. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.S.

A banded stack of euro banknotes, the paper currency of the European Union (EU). Color and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the euro sign, €. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the EU.

Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom (England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and Scotland). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple £20 notes with the pound sign, £.

A banded stack of U.S. dollar bills with feather wings, as if flying. Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair.

The backside of a credit card, showing the magnetic strip and signature. Color and detail vary across platforms, but often shown as gold, silver, or blue. May be used for banking and other ID cards as well for various content concerning money, including payment.

A white paper receipt, as proof of payment, and shown flat or curled. May be used for other financial documents (e.g., invoice, tax form). May also be used for the slang receipts, or "evidence” or “confirmation” of some feat or controversy.

The back of an envelope, as used to send a letter or card in the mail (post). Generally depicted in white, though Google’s design is yellow. Used for various content concerning mail and messages, including email.
A symbol for email. Depicted as the back of an envelope imprinted with a capital letter E (for electronic) or @ (at) sign. Commonly used as an icon before an email address.
The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines.
The back of envelope with a down arrow on top. Generally depicted in white (except for Google’s yellow design) with a red or blue arrow.
A paper tray with an up arrow on top, as a symbol for an email outbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden tray with a red arrow.
A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red or green arrow.
A package (parcel), as contains items ordered online. Depicted at various angles as a light-brown, cardboard box, with a shipping label and its top taped shut.

A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag raised. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag lowered. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag and white envelope (Google's design is yellow). Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan. May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom.

A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. Many platforms display a cross mark or check mark on the ballot to indicate a vote, though Apple and Facebook leave theirs blank.

A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and schooling.

The silver nib of a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Like 🖋️ Fountain Pen, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

A black fountain pen with a silver nib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. Like ✒️ Black Nib, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports).
A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint a picture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left.

A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling.

A white piece of paper with text written on it by a yellow pencil, positioned over the sheet, tip down, at a 45° angle. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, including signing (in sports).
A tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for a file on a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.

A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for an opened folder when using a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.
A set of tabbed dividers or file guides, as used to organize a card index or file box. Depicted with three or more multicolored tabs on manila paper.
A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page torn off from a daily desk calendar, displaying month and day on a white, square page.

A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. Displays month and day on a white, square page, curled up at the bottom right.
A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
A spiral-bound calendar. Generally depicted as a monthly calendar, with a red or blue header. Apple and Samsung’s pages are curled up at the bottom right, as to flip for a new month.

A card index, as a Rolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. Depicted as a black or gray rotating device with a contact card displayed, including a graphic and text.

A graph showing a red (or sometimes green) trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of increase, from numerical data to being metaphorically on the rise. May also represent trending content as well as facts, figures, and charts more generally.

A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of decrease, from numeral data to being metaphorically down. May also represent facts, figures, and charts more generally.

A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. Commonly used to represent various types of data, information, facts, figures, and charts more generally.

A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports.
A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right.
A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on a map. Generally depicted as an upright pin with a red, round head.
A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from a mobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles.
Two or more silver paper clips linked together, generally forming an inverted V. Microsoft’s design displays three paper clips.
A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic straightedge with length markings at a 45° angle.

A triangle or set square, as used by engineers or architects to draw straight lines at angles. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic right triangle with length markings, its hypotenuse to the right.

A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper or hair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. Commonly used for content concerning haircuts, fashion design, arts and crafts, and various senses of cutting.
A black or gray box with a label holder, containing card index dividers with multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files. Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid.
A metal filing cabinet, as used to organize and store file folders at an office. Depicted in black or gray with two drawers, handles, and label holders.
A wastebasket, as used to discard trash in an office. Generally depicted as a silver, wire-mesh container. Also known as a wastepaper basket, trash/garbage can, or rubbish bin.

A locked (closed) padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a secure internet connection, private account, or locked device. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle. WhatsApp’s design is silver.
An unlocked padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a non-secure connection or open access online. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle, as an open 🔒 Locked.

A locked (closed) padlock with a fountain pen or nib positioned at various angles in front of it. Vendors implement the same design as their 🔒 Locked and the same or similar design as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib.
A locked (closed) padlock with an upright key at its right. Vendors implement the same designs as their 🔒 Locked and 🔑 Key.

A key, as opens a door or lock. Depicted at a 45° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial").
An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a tarnished, silver skeleton key with an ornate, bowed head and two-toothed bit at the bottom left.
A claw hammer, as used for driving or removing nails. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.
An axe with a wooden handle and a metal blade. On many platforms the blade is red, like a fire axe.
A pickaxe, a tool with a curved spike for breaking up rocks in mining. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.

A hammer and pick, as used for breaking up rocks in mining, crossed in an X shape. Generally depicted as metal, mallet- and chisel-styled hammers with wooden handles. The heads of the tools face up, with the pick usually at the right. Often used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction.

A hammer and wrench, as kept in a toolbox, crossed in an X shape. Depicted with metal tools facing up, the hammer positioned at the upper left. Most vendors implement the same design as for their 🔨 Hammer and 🔧 Wrench.

A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. Generally depicted as double-edged with a brown or black, cross-shaped hilt and positioned at 45° angle, often with its tip at the lower left.
